<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910701-0012</DOCNO><DOCID>910701-0012.</DOCID><HL>   Financing Business:   Meritor Savings Bank</HL><DATE>07/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21</SO><CO>   MTOR</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, REPURCHASES, SWAPS (BBK)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   MERITOR SAVINGS BANK sweetened its debt-exchange offerwith new common shares in addition to cash for its 12%subordinated capital notes. The new offer adds 180 Meritorshares to the $240 in cash per $1,000 face amount of thenotes originally proposed in March. The Philadelphia-basedcompany said that if all $115 million of the notes aretendered, noteholders would receive 20.7 million shares, orabout 37% of currently outstanding shares. Meritor said ithas requested regulatory approval for the new offer as wellas a reduction in the required minimum level of acceptance to80% of the outstanding notes. Meritor said its previouscash-only offer didn't result in tenders of 90% of the notesrequired for the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.'s approval.Meritor shares closed Friday at 68.75 cents, up 3.125 cents,in national over-the-counter trading.</LP><TEXT/></DOC>